Sophomore Junior and Senior years In November of last year I was diagnosed as gifted with ADD I am in the process of getting my final IQ and intelligence scale evaluations to pinpoint exactly how I store and retrieve information best I have not received assistance at my school I did not qualify because I had not failed or gotten any D s in any of my classes However the ADD has had a significant impact on my grades This type of ADD is a strange combination in that I love to learn new things and assimilate new information quickly If it is challenging the more easily I can focus and learn the material If the material is not challenging I have a much harder time staying focused Where homework is concerned it is the most problematic Organizing the volume of work in AP classes is frustrating and exceptionally difficult despite many organizational tools My brain does not plan and organize well and it takes an enormous amount of effort The other aspect is that once I learn a new and challenging concept it is not new any longer and repetative tasks to solidify the information i e homework feel very mundane and redundant to me It is extremely difficult to focus and stay on track in these instances I have learned to set the environment to one that is ideal and have strategies in place to guide me through it However it remains difficult and takes me several times longer to get through information I already understand than it does to get through information that is new to me It is a positive thing in terms of loving to learn and enjoying challenging and interesting concepts It is the repetative that takes me a great deal longer to get through because I catch myself thinking about other things and have to refocus myself many times in order to complete my work I have made significant improvements in dealing with this however because I was diagnosed do late in high school and I have been able to maintain my grades above D s and F s it has significantly impacted my GPA As I hone my skills and continue to improve in effectively dealing with the ADD I fully expect to overcome it

Honor Society Academic Letter and PinIn third grade I sprained an ankle playing basketball triggering a neurological movement disorder called dystonia My ability to walk sit stand and simply move became increasingly difficult In a period of two years I went from being athletic and active to being uncomfortable and restricted My physical situation regressed to the point that I had to use crutches to walk and finally a wheelchair I remember my frustration anger and bitterness however my friends my family and my personality would not allow me to remain mired in a pool of depression After a plethora of doctor appointments myriad physical therapy sessions and three major operations I am fully independent of my wheelchair and have regained my ability to walk albeit with crutches Over the past decade the trials and tribulations I have experienced have shaped my personality and molded my character If I had never sprained my ankle in third grade and developed dystonia I would never have learned to empathize with others to have patience in difficult circumstances to embrace the gifts others take for granted and to remain optimistic despite the troubles of life In spite of my physical restrictions I have been able to accomplish prodigious achievements and met many friends along the way As a result my recommendations describe my effervescent personality and highlight my leadership qualities Throughout my struggles with dystonia I have remained upbeat and positive Perhaps it was these qualities that led to my selection of Homecoming King

years of experience Around age 9 I began playing the piano and taking lessons Once I started middle school however I changed instruments and became a flute player I will be going on my seventh year playing the flute In middle school I participated in both the concert band and the pep band Once in high school I played in the marching band and concert band I played in the marching band for 2 years until I became the drum major and led the band instead In concert band I started in the lower ensemble and was first chair flute That year I got braces put on in January With hard work and dedication I was able to play soon after and went on to receive a superior rating on my grade 4 solo Madrigal at District Solo and Ensemble At the end of the year we were able to audition for the top ensemble I went second and made it That next year I participated in marching band for the first half of the season Then in October we had chair placement auditions I was second chair flute behind a senior That December I had the first of two jaw surgeries I relearned how to play with a palette expander and a gap between my teeth during winter break and I was able to play once school started back up While I did not play a solo that year at solo and ensemble I did play a grade 4 trio and received a superior rating Later that year I also participated in Orchestra for the musical production The Wizard of Oz as first chair flute At the end of my Sophomore year I auditioned for drum major and got it The marching season of my junior year was a little bit different in that I no longer played on the field Instead I helped lead them under the wing of the senior drum major Chair placements were in November I auditioned and got first chair flute as a junior That year I also played a grade 5 solo Syrinx for district solo and ensemble and qualified for state solo and ensemble However the week prior to state I had my second jaw surgery I was out of commission for 6 weeks with an enormous white splint in my mouth The splint was finally removed in late April and within the next three weeks I was able to play the first flute part at the final concert I get my braces taken off in August this year and I will yet again have to learn how to replay but I am optimistic After all I have all of marching season to recover My jaw surgeries took a lot out of me but made me a better person They made me stronger more determined and more optimistic about outcomes of my life I find that one of my favorite qualities is my optimism That coupled with my intrinsic motivation has inspired me to do so much more than I ever thought I was capable of like score all fours and fives on the nine AP exams I have taken so far or graduate at the top of my class My positive attitude and motivation help me set the goals I aspire to accomplish like attend Vanderbilt University become a pediatric surgeon and eventually open up my own clinic

Lobbyist 10 Division I solo 10 11 Academic Letter every semester Local version of National Honor Society 12 Positives Truly passionate learner I am neither a grind nor do I complete only the bare minimum for the grade My supplemental letter of recommendation was excellent The teacher who wrote it knew me very well and really liked me and captured my personality quite well I thought I know that everyone says that their recs are great but mine are Double legacy at Princeton although of course I did not apply ED Hopefully I will still get a bit of a boost RD Essays were strong Main essay was about my love of books and reading I attempted to reveal my personality w o being too heavy handed and I think I did that I am a strong writer and have a defined voice in print and I think that this came across in my essays and short answers I had excellent interviews for Princeton Yale Brown and Carleton I pride myself on being well spoken and having an easy manner Female math major in Mulitvariable Calc who is also strong in the humanites minor plus maybe Negatives Weak extras for the Ivies probably I don t have much to say here I know now and have always known that they are pretty average but I never really cared to up the ante I don t think that they are terrible but certainly not ber impressive GPA rank not nearly as perfect as many but they are better within the context of my school than many might initally think I had a slightly rough transition during freshmen year receiving 2 3 of my B s then and permantantly depressing my rank and GPA Unweighted GPA without freshmen year 3 91 and rank 8 THOUGHTS I guess my admissions season went okay Obviously I didn t get into my top 4 choices so I can t say it went great but I m certainly going to a top tier elite college so I didn t tank either Perhaps this seems obvious but admissions to highly selective colleges is not based simply on raw intelligence anymore there are too many smart kids I think I m positive that my test scores and academic record prove that I am at least as smart if not smarter than the average Yale Princeton etc student but obviously I couldn t hold up in the other areas especially extras My extras weren t terrible but it doesn t take much to fall out of the mere 7 of admitted RD applicants at these schools I would say to focus on schools that are still excellent and elite but where for a variety of reasons the door is open just a little bit wider For example Wellesley doesn t have as deep of an applicant pool because it s a women s college and they are thin on midwesterners and no one else from my HS applied All these things made my path much easier at Wellesley Apply to a variety of schools and be realistic if you don t have a top 10 rank don t apply to a bunch of schools where that is basically a requirement for admission because unless you are a true star in some other way you are basically not going to get in Keep your head up acceptance waitlist rejection letters don t prove how smart not smart you are or your worth as a person Finally remember that nobody cares as much as you do right now My parents both went to Princeton and I can promise you this didn t allow them to breeze through life without any worries There were still plenty of hard times monetary and otherwise We are comfortably upper middle class now but my parents worked hard and I can assure you that our neighborhood is NOT filled with only Ivy grads Honestly I will go out on a limb and say that if making money is your number one priority an elite education might be a waste for you There s no judgment intended in that statement just my belief that an elite school is primarily about the learning Sure you ll meet lots of well off grads of Ivies and other top Universities and LACs but those people were probably already pretty well off when they enrolled Hard work trumps a fancy name on your degree promise

web design to prepare them for studio employment I teach adobe flash dreamweaver and photoshop This is a copy of my personal statement Growing up I had to cope with rude comments staring eyes and peoplea s whispers that others thought I couldn t hear Initially it bothered me a little not because I necessarily cared about their opinion but because I thought it was unfair to criticize make remarks about people one hardly knows especially when that person is the one human being I love the most and care for unconditionally My one year old brother was diagnosed with autism on the eve of my fifth birthday I didna t fully realize what that diagnosis entailed and even less did I know that it would come to shape me into who I am as a person in the future My brother Aram had therapy six days a week right after school until late in the afternoon I would watch him struggle with concepts that were too complex for him and try answering questions he hardly comprehended As school grew more difficult and I became frustrated with my studies Aram was always on my mind How could I give up when I have such an advantage over him and he keeps trying When I failed at anything my parents were always gracious enough to remind me that I was capable of much better When I didn t want to do my homework or practice piano I would walk into the next room to see him struggling over the concepts of a morea and a lessa or a strangersa and a familya He inspires me to never take anything I have for granted His autism exposed me to a world of people with disabilities I would go to parent meetings and events dedicated to families of people who shared in this struggle I became acquainted with children who have severe social issues it brought me joy to a make their daya by talking and playing with them or even waving and smiling I befriended the immobile nonverbal and aggressive alike and came to see people for everything that they were and not how they spoke or looked or behaved By the time I was in middle school I was deeply involved with that world In middle school I attended 2 years of animation class where I learned how to design characters make storyboards and use Adobe Flash to animate then Maya to animate in 3 D After middle school a family friend and past President of the Foothill Autism Alliance told my mom about Media Enrichment Academy MEA an organization that specialized in teaching children with autism to animate She called and asked if we would be interested in enrolling my brother or if I was interested in learning more since I knew animation I visited and later volunteered there I became a weekly volunteer for a year and a half It was very gratifying helping others like my brother and to have their families be so thankful I was helping their children do something productive with their lives Soon the company broke into two and I began volunteering during the summer for Exceptional Minds where adults with autism would attend after high school so that they could learn the skills they needed to get jobs in the future I became and still am very passionate about this organization because I feel like it gives hope to people like my brother and I feel I am actually making a difference in the world It is my greatest hope that my brother could be capable enough to somehow make it in this world and to be able to be as much a functioning member of society as anyone else After two summers of volunteering every day I was offered a job there ita s almost a dream job to me I know the students are always happy to see me and I very pleased that I can make them feel comfortable even if normally theya re very self conscious of the fact that they are different I thank my brother every day for making me into a better more accepting person and for teaching me more about life than I could teach him
